sidebyside.p:
Since spherically distributed charge densiy has a spherical symmetry, we apply Gauss's law to easily get the magnitude of electric field. 

	E(r) = \begin{cases}
				0 \amp r \lt R\\
				\dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\,\dfrac{q}{r^2} \amp r \gt R
			\end{cases}

The direction of the electric field will be radially outward from the center of the sphere.

With P outside, we get the same expression for potential as that of a point charge, but in the space inside the sphere, we get constant potential. These are sketched in 

	\phi(r) = \begin{cases}
				\dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\,\dfrac{q}{R} \amp r \le R\\
				\dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\,\dfrac{q}{r} \amp r \gt R
			\end{cases}

solution.p:
(a) The given charge distributions have spherical symmetry.  Therefore, a quick application of Gauss's law yields the following for the electric field in various regions.

	\vec E = \begin{cases}
		0	\amp 	r\lt 4\:\text{cm}\\
		\dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\:\dfrac{5\:\mu\text{C}}{r^2}\: \hat u_r	\amp   \ \ \ \ 4\:\text{cm} \lt r \lt  6\:\text{cm}\\
		0	\amp 	 6\:\text{cm} \lt r \lt 8\:\text{cm}\\
		\dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\:\dfrac{-3\:\mu\text{C}}{r^2}\: \hat u_r	\amp  \ \ \ \    r > 8\:\text{cm}
	\end{cases}

(b) Using the isolation of electric field inside a metal cavity from outside, we can rewrite the results of part (a).  Now, we need to make sure that the distances outside the metal sphere will be from the center of the sphere but the distance at points inside the metal will be from the center of the cavity.   


	\vec E = \begin{cases}
		0	\amp 	r_{\text{in}} \lt 4\:\text{cm}\\
		\dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\:\dfrac{5\:\mu\text{C}}{r_{\text{in}}^2}\: \hat u_r	\amp   \ \ \ \ 4\:\text{cm} \lt  r_{\text{in}} \lt 5\:\text{cm}\\
		0	\amp 	 6\:\text{cm} \lt r_{\text{out}} \lt 8\:\text{cm}\\
		\dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\:\dfrac{-3\:\mu\text{C}}{r_{\text{out}}^2}\: \hat u_r	\amp  \ \ \ \    r_{\text{out}} > 8\:\text{cm}
	\end{cases}
